         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility"> ¶ Among the Restiaceae last sent by Mr. Buchanan ¶  is a female specimen of the tall species peculiar to the Chatham Islands. ¶  Unexpectedly it shows this plant to belong to, the nucular, not the ca...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">73.12.00a</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To James Hector</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Letter not found. The text given here is from the Proceedings of the Wellington Philosophical Society (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">Transactions and proceedings of the New Zealand Institute</seg>
                     <seg style="">, vol. 6, p. 389 (B74.06.03). The item is dated to December 1873 as the latest likely date that it could have been written and read at the meeting </seg>of 6 January 1874. The text is introduced by </p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0.5in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.1665in; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Dr. Hector read the following extract from a letter received from Baron von Mueller, relative to a plant from the Chatham Islands, described in "Fragmenta Phytographiae Australiensis," (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">sic</seg>) LXII., p, 79, as <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Lepyrodia">Lepyrodia</name> traversii</seg>, which further specimens have proved to be a new genus— [See B73.08.01, p. 79].</p>
               </note>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Among the <name key="Restiaceae">Restiaceae</name> last sent by Mr. Buchanan<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>John Buchanan (1819-1898).</p>
               </note> is a female specimen of the tall species peculiar to the Chatham Islands.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See M to J. Hector, July 1873 (in this edition as 73-07-00a).</p>
               </note> Unexpectedly it shows this plant to belong to, the nucular, not the capsular, series of the genera, among which its dispersion of flowers places it separate from any, except the South African genus <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                  <name key="Elegia">Elegia</name>
               </seg>; but, as it differs in various respects from all the specimens of that genus, and as we have no <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                  <name key="Elegia">Elegia</name>s</seg> out of Africa, I have deemed it best to form a separate genus for the Chatham Island plant, and have named this new genus <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                  <name key="Sporadanthus">Sporadanthus</name>
               </seg>.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See P. Lange et al. </seg>(1999) for a discussion of the history of the taxon.</p>
               </note> It holds precisely the same relation to <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                  <name key="Leptocarpus">Leptocarpus</name>
               </seg> as <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                  <name key="Lepyrodia">Lepyrodia</name>
               </seg> to <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                  <name key="Restio">Restio</name>
               </seg>. Perhaps you will kindly Insert a brief note to this effect in your next volume.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Elegia">Elegia</name>
            </p>
